    </header>

    <div class="explorer-mobile-notice" role="note">
      <p>On a phone, the grid is still usable, but it reads best if you start with the guide below and then scroll the matrix horizontally.</p>
      <div class="explorer-mobile-actions">
        <a href="#explore" class="btn ghost">Open the grid</a>
        <a href="/api-explorer" class="btn secondary">Use the API view</a>
        <a href="/memo/data-counterfactuals" class="btn ghost">Read the memo first</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="explorer-help-stack" aria-label="Grid page guide">
      <details class="explorer-help-drawer">
        <summary>What scenario are we simulating here?</summary>
        <div class="explorer-help-body">
          <p>We are imagining one model builder working inside a tiny universe of possible data items or slices named A, B, C, D, and so on.</p>
          <p>Each row is one possible training world. Each column is one possible evaluation slice. One cell means: train on the row world, then evaluate on the column slice.</p>
          <p>The point of the toy is not realism. It is to make the comparison structure visible enough that you can see exactly which counterfactual worlds are being contrasted.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="explorer-help-drawer">
        <summary>How to read the grid?</summary>
        <div class="explorer-help-body" set:html={introSection.html}></div>
      </details>

      <details class="explorer-help-drawer">
        <summary>How to interact with this page</summary>
        <div class="explorer-help-body">
          <p>Start by choosing a question family and a cell score. Then click a row, a column, or a cell to anchor the train/eval pair you care about.</p>
          <p>The current reading, marker tools, and mode controls all stay tied to that same selection. Example scenes can jump you into useful presets without changing the overall mental model.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="explorer-help-drawer">
        <summary>What are all the ML concepts we can explore with this grid?</summary>
        <div class="explorer-help-body">
          <p>The grid supports direct cell reading, leave-one-out, group leave-one-out, Shapley value, Banzhaf value, Beta Shapley, scaling laws, toy differential privacy, toy unlearning, and toy poisoning.</p>
          <ul class="explorer-help-list">
            <li><code>Explore</code> reads one train/eval world pair directly.</li>
            <li><code>LOO</code> and <code>Group LOO</code> compare nearby training worlds after removing one point or a coalition.</li>
            <li><code>Shapley</code>, <code>Banzhaf</code>, and <code>Beta Shapley</code> average marginal contributions across many partial worlds.</li>
            <li><code>Scaling</code> averages rows by training-set size, while <code>DP</code>, <code>Unlearning</code>, and <code>Poison</code> reinterpret the same space through privacy, deletion, and attack lenses.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>

    <section class="section-card explorer-frame" id="explore" aria-label="Explore">
      <div class="explorer-shell">
        <Explorer client:load />
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
